04787nam a22006735i 9780226545615DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017028653  a97802265456157 a10.7208/97802265456152doi  a(DE-B1597)568251  a(OCoLC)1198931425  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBR500b.E35 2018 4aBR500b.E35 2018 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a322/.12231 aJohnson, Paul Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEkklesia :bThree Inquiries in Church and State /cPaul Christopher Johnson, Winnifred Fallers Sullivan, Pamela E. Klassen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTRIOS00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tTHE PEOPLE AND THE LAW OF THE HOUND AT CANUDOS -- tSPIRITUAL JURISDICTIONS -- tBANNING BIBLES -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEkklesia: Three Inquiries in Church and State offers a New World rejoinder to the largely Europe-centered academic discourse on church and state. In contrast to what is often assumed, in the Americas the relationship between church and state has not been one of freedom or separation but one of unstable and adaptable collusion. Ekklesia sees in the settler states of North and South America alternative patterns of conjoined religious and political power, patterns resulting from the undertow of other gods, other peoples, and other claims to sovereignty. These local challenges have led to a continuously contested attempt to realize a church-minded state, a state-minded church, and the systems that develop in their concert. The shifting borders of their separation and the episodic conjoining of church and state took new forms in both theory and practice. The first of a closely linked trio of essays is by Paul Johnson, and offers a new interpretation of the Brazilian community gathered at Canudos and its massacre in 1896–97, carried out as a joint churchstate mission and spectacle. In the second essay, Pamela Klassen argues that the colonial churchstate relationship of Canada came into being through local and national practices that emerged as Indigenous nations responded to and resisted becoming “possessions” of colonial British America. Finally, Winnifred Sullivan’s essay begins with reflection on the increased effort within the United States to ban Bibles and scriptural references from death penalty courtrooms and jury rooms; she follows with a consideration of the political theological pressure thereby placed on the jury that decides between life and death. Through these three inquiries, Ekklesia takes up the familiar topos of “church and state” in order to render it strange.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChurch and statezBrazil. 0aChurch and statezCanada. 0aChurch and statezUnited States. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aCanudos.  aNew World.  achurch.  adeath penalty.  astate.  athe people.1 aFallers Sullivan, Winnifred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Paul Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlassen, Pamela E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKlassen, Pamela E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSullivan, Winnifred Fallers, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226545615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/978022